param.name: title
param.value: Hunting Signatures of Cryovolcanism on Charon

param.name: abstract
param.value:
Charon, the largest moon of the dwarf planet Pluto, is a fascinating object, one of the very few trans-Neptunian objects large enough for us to be able to study the ices of its surface. These ices imprint absorption bands on Charon's reflected solar spectrum, which is dominated by water ice. However, near-infrared observations of Charon have shown a 2.21 micron absorption band, attributed to ammonia. Ammonia decreases the melting point of a water ice mix: a sufficiently large TNO, heated during its accretion, could once have had an internal ocean. These may be the signature of ancient cryovolcanic lavas.
Unfortunately, this single observed line is ambiguous: its position could be strongly influenced by the ice grains' size and shape. It only provides tantalising evidence for this geophysically important molecule, not confirmation of its presence. Detecting a stronger second line would provide this proof. Laboratory studies show that the deeper fundamental line of ammonia sits at 3-3.1 microns, in L-band.
We propose to observe Charon with GNIRS and AO to obtain an L-band spectrum that will decisively confirm if ammonia is present on Charon's surface. This proposal is part of the thesis of the PI.

param.name: NoteText
param.value:
The spectral feature of science interest is at 3.0-3.1 microns, so a wavelength shift of up to ~10% should not be a problem.
Pluto and Charon are <0.7" apart, so Pluto (H=14 or so) will dominate. The slit should be aligned to capture both (ie. the satellite orbital plane is along the slit), so the position angle will need to be set according to the lookup table of when you're taking the data, and adjusted when re-acquiring. When guiding on Pluto, Charon will move perpendicular to the slit by about 0.04 arcsec (~1 pixel) per hour. The PA table is a Note in each of the science observations.
Please send email once the data are taken :)
-Michele Bannister (PI)

If the observation is scheduled as both blocks together on one night, please observe both the "before" and "after" tellurics.
If it is broken into single blocks on separate nights, please observe only one of the tellurics, choosing the one most appropriate to be closest to the mean airmass of Pluto/Charon.

param.name: NoteText
param.value:
On-source exposure times for "long red camera without AO" acquisitions were calculated by adding 2.5mag to the source magnitude, and using the online table for 3-5 micron science.
Because the OT complains when red camera acquisitions are done in H, the slit image and acq exposures take place in the K filter. The slit image exposure time was scaled from the nominal 15s at H (from the "LS, 111 l/mm, 0.05"/pix, LM" OT Library example) to 24s at K, based on the ratio of sky+telescope detector well half-filling times for H and K in the "long camera, 0.1" slit, non-AO, 110 l/mm" mode (i.e., 5000s versus 8000s).
The science is at L.
The deep well mode is used for the acquisition to avoid detector instabilities associated with changing the bias.
C. Onken, 4 July 2011 Australian Gemini Office

param.name: NoteText
param.value:
On-source exposure times for "long red camera without AO" acquisitions were calculated by adding 2.5mag to the source magnitude, and using the online table for 3-5 micron science.
Because the OT complains when red camera acquisitions are done in H, the slit image and acq exposures take place in the K filter. The slit image exposure time was scaled from the nominal 15s at H (from the "LS, 111 l/mm, 0.05"/pix, LM" OT Library example) to 24s at K, based on the ratio of sky+telescope detector well half-filling times for H and K in the "long camera, 0.1" slit, non-AO, 110 l/mm" mode (i.e., 5000s versus 8000s).
For Pluto, the table suggests an exposure time of 1x24s (plus a sky frame) is appropriate at H-band in the long red camera without AO. As this is far from the 100s integration limit in H, and the K background should not be too dissimilar from H, the 24s exposure time is used here at K.
The science is at L.
The deep well mode is used for the acquisition to avoid detector instabilities associated with changing the bias.
C. Onken, 4 July 2011 Australian Gemini Office
